text: The first antibiotic identified from an actinomycete, streptomycin, was discovered in the middle of last century. Since then, many new chemical structures with strong anti-infective and anticancer activities have been identified from the secondary metabolites of actinomycetes, which have been recognized as an important source for the development of new antibiotic agents. The structures of the new compounds were elucidated by comprehensive spectral data analysis. Compounds 2 and 4 exhibited antitumor activity against human cancer cells MDA‑MB‑435, MDA‑MB‑231, NCI-H460, HCT-116 and HepG2, and human normal breast epithelial cell MCF10A with IC50 values ranging from 0.4 to 6.9 µM. identified from marine actinomycetes since the last decade of the 20th century [5, 6]. Previously, we reported cytotoxic grincamycins (GCNs) from the South China Sea-derived actinomycete Streptomyces lusitanus SCSIO LR32 (Streptomycetaceae), which was isolated from sedi- ment collected at a depth of − 3370 m [7, 8]. Recently, the strain SCSIO LR32 was cultivated again on a 27 L-scale. Besides the dom- inant products GCN and GCNs B–F, three new angucyclines desig- nated grincamycin I (1), J (2), and K (3) (▶ Fig. 1), as well as a known compound A-7884 (4), were purified from the fermenta- tion extract as minor metabolites. The structures of the new com- pounds were elucidated on the basis of MS and 1D and 2D NMR data analyses. Structurally, the skeleton of grincamycins I (1) and J (2) belongs to the urdamycin B-type angucyclines, while grinca- mycin K (3) is a non-classical vineomycinone B2-type angucycline. In this paper, we report the isolation and structural elucidation of the three new angucycline glycosides (1–3), as well as the cyto- toxicity of compounds 1–4 isolated from the deep sea-derived strain SCSIO LR32.

Strain SCSIO LR32 was fermented using modified RA medium on rotary shakers [7]. The harvested culture was centrifuged to yield mycelium and broth. The mycelial cake was extracted with ace- tone to afford a residue after solvent evaporation. The residue was purified through column chromatography (CC) over normal phase silica gel and semi-preparative HPLC to yield compounds 1–4. The structure of compound 4 was identified by comparing the MS, 1H, and 13C NMR spectroscopic data with those of A- 7884 [9]. HR‑ESI‑MS and NMR spectra of grincamycins I (1), J (2), and K (3) are available as Supporting Information.

Grincamycin I (1) was isolated as a red amorphous powder. The molecular formula C49H60O16 was determined by negative mode HR‑ESI‑MS (Fig. 1S, Supporting Information) at m/z 903.3823 [M −, 903.3809) along with – H]− (calculated [calcd] for C49H59O16 analysis of NMR data. The IR spectrum of 1 showed hydroxy groups at 3402, 3383, and 3275 cm−1, carbonyl groups at 1728, 1716, and 1670 cm−1, and aromatic rings at 1630 and 1591 cm−1. The 1H and 13C NMR spectroscopic data (▶ Table 1) re- vealed that 1 contained a similar aromatic aglycone, as well as the same sugar substituted pattern at the 3- and 9-position as those of the previously reported GCN (Table 1S, Supporting Informa- tion) [7]. In the low field region, one chelated hydroxy group (δH 12.56, 8-OH) and two pairs of ortho-coupled aromatic protons (δH 7.51, 8.24, J = 7.9 Hz, H-5, 6; δH 7.83, 7.61, J = 7.9 Hz, H-10, 11) were apparent based on HMBC correlations (Fig. 8S, Support- ing Information) as shown in ▶ Fig. 2. However, the differences between the NMR data of 1 and GCN were that the 13C NMR sig- nals for two oxygen-bearing quaternary carbons at δC 77.2 and 79.7 in GCN were missing, and two olefinic quaternary carbons at δC 147.6 (C-4a) and 135.8 (C-12b) were observed in 1. In addi- tion, 13C NMR resonances of C-1 and C-4 in ring A were shifted up- field from δC 204.7 and 44.1 in GCN to δC 197.2 and 42.0

b) were observed in 1. In addi- tion, 13C NMR resonances of C-1 and C-4 in ring A were shifted up- field from δC 204.7 and 44.1 in GCN to δC 197.2 and 42.0 in 1, re- spectively. Moreover, the 13C NMR data of C-5 and C-12a in ring B were also shifted upfield in 1 compared with GCN. These changes suggested that the single bond between C-4a and C-12b in GCN

was replaced by an olefinic double bond in 1, which was further confirmed on the basis of HMBC correlations from H-4, H-5, and H-6 to C-4a, and from H-2, H-4, and H-5 to C-12b. Furthermore, five anomeric methine signals (δC 70.9, δH 4.84, CH‑A1; δC 99.5, δH 4.94, CH‑B1; δC 99.0, δH 5.03, CH‑C1; δC 91.7, δH 5.05, CH‑D1, and δC 99.0, δH 4.94, CH‑E1) were observed along with another nine methine, nine methylene, five doublet methyl, and two carbonyl signals, which were almost identical to those of the two sugar chains found in GCN, indicating the presence of a tri- saccharide comprising β-olivose, α-rhodinose, and α-cinerulose A, and a disaccharide consisting of α-rhodinose and α-cinerulose A [7]. The C-glycosidic bond of C‑A1/C-9 between the trisaccha- ride and aglycone was confirmed by HMBC correlations from the anomeric proton of β-olivose (H‑A1) to C-8 (δC 158.0), C-9 (δC 136.7), and C-10 (δC 133.7) of the aglycone, and from H-10 to C‑A1. The position of the O-glycosidic bond between the agly- cone and the disaccharide was deduced by 3JC–H long range cou- pling of H‑D1/C-3. The relative configuration of the sugar residues was further confirmed by NOESY experiment (▶ Fig. 3 and Fig. 9S, Supporting Information). Grincamycin K (3) was isolated as a yellowish amorphous pow- der. A molecular formula of C31H34O12 was established from the HR‑ESI‑MS peak (Fig. 3S, Supporting Information) at m/z 597.1990 [M – H]− (calcd for 597.1978). The 1H and 13C NMR spectroscopic data of 3 resembled those of GCN C (Table 2S, Sup- porting Information) [7], except for the sugar moiety signals, sug- gesting 3 had the same aglycone as GCN C. Two pairs of ortho- coupled aromatic proton signals were observed at δH 7.55, 7.58 (H-3, 4) and δH 7.76, 7.66 (J = 7.7 Hz, H-7, 8) (▶ Table 1). Accordingly, only two anomeric methines (δC 71.1, δH 4.78, CH‑A1; δC 99.2, δH 5.11, CH‑B1), two methyls (δC 18.2, δH 1.31, Me-A6; δC 14.4, δH 1.25, Me-B6), and a carbonyl (δC 210.5), to- gether with another four methines and three methylenes were re- vealed by the 1H, 13C, and HMQC spectra, disclosing the existence of a disaccharide consisting of β-olivose and α-cinerulose A. The HMBC correlations of H‑A4/C‑B1 and H‑B1/C‑A4 indicated a C‑B1-O-C‑A4 connection between the two deoxy sugars. The C- glycosidic bond C-9/C-A1 between the aglycone and β-olivose was deduced from the HMBC correlations of H‑A1/C‑6, C-7. NOESY data (Fig. 21S, Supporting Information) supported the rel- ative configuration of the sugar residues (▶ Fig. 3). In the same fashion as 1, the absolute configuration of C-12 in 3 was proposed to be R, which was identical to that in GCN C.

Cytotoxic activities of compounds 1–4 were evaluated against a panel of five human tumor cell lines using the MTT method [10], including human melanocyte cancer cells MDA‑MB‑435, high metastatic human breast cancer cells MDA‑MB‑231, large cell lung cancer cells NCI-H460, human colorectal cancer cells HCT- 116, human hepatocellular cells HepG2, and the non-cancerous human breast epithelial cell line MCF10A. As depicted in ▶ Table 2, grincamycin J (2) and A-7884 (4) showed cytotoxicities against lines with IC50 values ranging from 0.4 to the six human cell 6.9 µM. Grincamycin I (1) exhibited moderate cytotoxic activities on the panel of five human cancer cell lines. However, grincamy- cin I (1) also showed strong cytotoxicity against normal human breast epithelial cells MCF10A with an IC50 value of 2.9 µM, almost the same as those of 2 and 4. Grincamycin K (3) did not show cy- totoxic activity at a concentration of 50 µM. From the results de- scribed in ▶ Table 2, it was inferred that the classical angucyclines possessed higher cytotoxic activities than the non-classical tri- cyclic vinemycinone-B2 type angucycline, revealing that ring A in the angular position is necessary for cytotoxicity in vitro. However, grincamycin J (2) and A-7884 (4) exhibited more potent cytotoxicity than 1, indicating the absence of the di- saccharide at 3-O-position helps to enhance the cytotoxic activity. Furthermore, 2 and 4 almost showed the same cytotoxicity, indi- cating that the terminal sugar in the trisaccharide chain and the hydroxy groups at 4a and 12a have no effect on cytotoxic activity. In addition, compounds 1–4 were tested for their antimicrobial effects against Micrococcus luteus, Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 29 213, Bacillus thuringiensis, and methicillin-resistant S. aureus (shhs-A1). Only A-7884 (4) exhibited growth inhibition against M. luteus with a MIC value of 1.95 µg/mL. Compounds 1–3 did not show any antibacterial activities at a concentration of 100 µg/mL. Three new angucycline compounds, grincamycin I (1), J (2), and K (3), together with the known A-7884 (4), were isolated and iden- tified from deep sea-derived S. lusitanus SCSIO LR32. Among those compounds, grincamycin J (2) showed potent cytotoxicity against a panel of human cancer cell lines in biological assays. The analysis of structure-activity relationships revealed that classi- cal angucyclines possessed higher cytotoxic activity than non- classical tricyclic vinemycinone-B2 type angucyclines. Further- more, the absence of 3-O-glycosylation in classical angucycline enhances the cytotoxicity.

So far, different angucyclines have been obtained from the wild type of S. lusitanus SCSIO LR32, including aquayamycin-type (GCN, A7884, P-1894B [vineomycin A1], saquayamycin B), urda- mycin B-type (GCNs I and J), galtamycin-type (GCNs E, G, H), vine- omycinone B2-type (GCNs B, C, D, K, vineomycin B2) compounds, as well as several angucycline congeners that have been identified from genetically modified mutants of SCSIO LR32 constructed during the biosynthetic investigation of grincamycin and P- 1894B [7, 8, 11], revealing that S. lusitanus SCSIO LR32 is a prolific strain in providing diverse angucycline glycosides. The mycelial cake was stirred and extracted by acetone three times. The organic layer was evaporated to dryness under vacuum to yield the crude ex- tract. The extract was subjected to CC on silica gel and fraction- ated using gradient elution with CHCl3–MeOH (100 : 0, 99 : 1, 97 : 3, 95 : 5, 90 : 10, 80 : 20, and 0 : 100, v/v) to afford seven frac- tions (Fr.A1~Fr.A7). After HPLC analysis, Fr.A2 was purified by SiO2 CC eluting with a mixture of petroleum ether and EtOAc (80 : 20, 70 : 30, 65 : 35, 60 : 40, 50 : 50, 30 : 70, 0 : 100, v/v) to give seven fractions (Fr.B1~Fr.B7). Separation of Fr.B3 was achieved using semi-preparative HPLC (gradient of 40 % CH3CN to 100 % CH3CN over 20 min, followed by 100 % CH3CN for 8 min, 2.5 mL/min) to yield 1 (16.8 mg), 2 (7.3 mg), 3 (7.7 mg), and 4 (7.4 mg).

HCT-116, HepG2, and MCF10A cells were determined using the MTT method. All cell lines were purchased from the ATCC. Briefly, tumor cell lines were cultured at a density of 1 × 104 cells/well at 37 °C in a humidified incubator (5 % CO2) for 24 h, followed by testing for 48 h in various concentrations of the compounds. Then 20 µL of 3-(4,5-dimethyl-2-thiazolyl)-2,5-diphenyl-2-H-tetrazo- lium bromide (MTT) solution was added to each well and incu- bated for 4 h. Culture supernatant was removed and replaced by 150 µL of dimethyl sulfoxide in each well. Cell growth inhibition was determined by measuring absorbance and calculated using the formula: cell viability (%) = (the average A550 nm of the treated group/the average A550 nm of the untreated group) × 100. Three independent repeated trials were conducted for each compound (n = 3). IC50 values and 95 % confidence interval (CI) were esti- mated using Excelʼs forecast and confidence functions (Microsoft Excel 2007) [10]. The antibacterial activities of compounds 1–4 were assessed against M. luteus, S. aureus ATCC 29 213, B. thuringiensis, and me- thicillin-resistant S. aureus (shhs-A1) using a sequential two-fold serial dilution method. Compounds were dissolved in DMSO, seri- ally diluted in Mueller-Hinton (M‑H) broth. The test was con- ducted in triplicate in a 96-well plate. Kanamycin and ampicillin were used as positive controls. DMSO in M‑H broth was used as blank control [12]. HR‑ESI‑MS and NMR spectra of grincamycins I (1), J (2), and K (3) are available as Supporting Information.
